    "description": "Soft black cylindrical foam body with domed top.",
    "justification": "In Italy throughout the 1960s and 1970s, radical design groups were established in opposition to the functionalism of the International Style. Gruppo Strum was one of these groups. They were active in Torino, Italy, between 1966 and 1975, taking their name as an abbreviation of archtettura strumentale (functional architecture). The founders were all architects, graduates of Politecnico di Torino: Giorgio Ceretti, Pietro Derossi, Carlo Giammarco, Riccardo Rosso, and Maurizio Vogliazzo. The group promoted theoretical studies and seminars that played a role in development of the antidesign and radical architecture movements.\nThe Puffo stool is made from a polyurethane foam that has been molded into a simple cylinder. What looks like a rigid, almost bullet-like form is actually a soft, pliable mass that yields to the sitter while it supports.\nThis stool would add to a small group of Italian pop art design in the museum\u2019s collection, including the foam Cactus coat rack manufactured by Gufram and furniture of other materials by designers such as Gaetano Pesce.",
